  "transcript": {
    "language": "en",
    "is_generated": true,
    "source": "whisper_local",
    "segments": [
      {
        "start": 0.0,
        "duration": 8.0,
        "text": "Most of the code we've written comes in the form of programs and scripts, meaning there are sets of instructions that perform a specific job."
      },
      {
        "start": 8.9,
        "duration": 4.9,
        "text": "But most of the technology we interact with comes in the form of software."
      },
      {
        "start": 14.7,
        "duration": 6.8,
        "text": "Instead of a single program, software is a system of programs and data that work together over time."
      },
      {
        "start": 22.6,
        "duration": 5.8,
        "text": "For example, video editing software doesn't perform just one job. It performs many."
      },
      {
        "start": 29.3,
        "duration": 5.5,
        "text": "Like smoothing the audio, overlaying text, or adding transitions in between clips."
      },
      {
        "start": 36.1,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "The code that makes up a piece of software doesn't all execute at the same time."
      },
      {
        "start": 42.2,
        "duration": 11.4,
        "text": "Instead, software reacts to events. For example, when you open up a game, it doesn't just run through every possible thing that could happen in the game from start to finish."
      },
      {
        "start": 54.2,
        "duration": 5.6,
        "text": "But rather, it executes specific pieces of code in response to specific events."
      },
      {
        "start": 60.9,
        "duration": 4.3,
        "text": "Like when the user presses a button, the game may change the character's direction."
      },
      {
        "start": 66.6,
        "duration": 4.2,
        "text": "Or when the character runs into an item, the game may enable a power up."
      },
      {
        "start": 72.2,
        "duration": 3.8,
        "text": "Or when a timer runs out, the game may toggle the current mode."
      },
      {
        "start": 76.7,
        "duration": 8.8,
        "text": "Ultimately, this means a piece of software has thousands of lines of code that manage tons of data and tons of functionality together."
      },
      {
        "start": 86.7,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "As a programmer then, how do we keep track of all that complexity in our hits?"
      },
      {
        "start": 92.7,
        "duration": 3.4,
        "text": "The answer is, we don't. We use abstraction."
      },
      {
        "start": 97.3,
        "duration": 6.6,
        "text": "In programming, abstraction is the process of hiding unnecessary details so we can focus on what matters."
      },
      {
        "start": 104.9,
        "duration": 3.1,
        "text": "A function, for example, is a form of abstraction."
      },
      {
        "start": 109.0,
        "duration": 3.4,
        "text": "If I want to perform this task, I can just call this function."
      },
      {
        "start": 113.2,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "As soon as I trust the people I work with, I don't need to understand how this code works in order to use it."
      },
      {
        "start": 120.1,
        "duration": 3.1,
        "text": "Functions, however, just let us abstract behavior."
      },
      {
        "start": 123.8,
        "duration": 3.6,
        "text": "But in software, we also need to abstract data."
      },
      {
        "start": 128.2,
        "duration": 8.8,
        "text": "To make our code more intuitive to work with, we want our software to think about things the same way that humans do."
      },
      {
        "start": 137.7,
        "duration": 2.7,
        "text": "So, same building the school management software."
      },
      {
        "start": 141.0,
        "duration": 3.0,
        "text": "That software needs to represent real things."
      },
      {
        "start": 144.6,
        "duration": 2.9,
        "text": "Like students, teachers, classrooms, assignments."
      },
      {
        "start": 148.4,
        "duration": 4.2,
        "text": "I can create a bunch of different data structures that group different bits of data."
      },
      {
        "start": 153.6,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "And I can create a bunch of modules that group a bunch of functions that perform a bunch of tasks."
      },
      {
        "start": 159.9,
        "duration": 0.8,
        "text": "Does this work?"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.5,
        "duration": 0.3,
        "text": "Yes."
      },
      {
        "start": 162.6,
        "duration": 4.6,
        "text": "But it's pretty challenging to work with as the size of our software grows."
      },
      {
        "start": 169.0,
        "duration": 4.6,
        "text": "Why not organize our code in a way that better mirrors the real world?"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.9,
        "duration": 3.3,
        "text": "Like a student has their own data."
      },
      {
        "start": 178.2,
        "duration": 3.6,
        "text": "Like their name, their email address, their core schedule, their grades."
      },
      {
        "start": 182.8,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "And each student can take actions like enrolling a class or submit an assignment."
